issue.body:
Hi,

I would like to Abort the script execution.

For example:
```js
If ( testObjects.totalCount===0) {
//1. .......
//2. abort("No Data Found") ; 
//3. ...........
}
```

If i use abort in this case then it should abort the script Immediately regardless of duration whatever i have specified.

Currently i'm using fail but the script is getting executed till i specified the duration (which doesn't serve my purpose).

Could someone please get this implemented ?

Thanks,
Rushabh

body:
We discussed this a bit internally, and this is the specification we arrived at:

- The function name should be `abortTest()` and it should be in the root `k6` JS module (i.e. it should be accessible from test scripts via `import { abortTest } from 'k6'`).
- Once called, `abortTest()` should stop the whole test run and the k6 process should exit with a custom fixed non-zero exit code `107`.
- In contrast to the old way of stopping the test run (a threshold on a custom metric with `abortOnFail: true`) mentioned above, `abortTest()` should make sure that the VU that called it stops immediately after, i.e. no more instructions from its current iteration are executed and no more iterations are started. 
- The `teardown()` function should still be executed after the test run aborts in this way.
- The run status of the test run should be [`aborted by script`](https://github.com/loadimpact/k6/blob/9d973f564f5a8e3754fa51be4b22a03295cbae9e/lib/collector.go#L47) (e.g. for when `k6 run --out cloud` is used)

So, a JS script that uses it should look somewhat like this:

```js
import http from 'k6/http';
import { abortTest, sleep } from 'k6';

export default function () {
    // ... some test logic ...
    if (Math.random() < 0.01) { // or some actual test abort check
        console.log('mayday, mayday');
        abortTest();
        console.log('this should never be executed');
    }
    // ...
}
```

issue.body:
Closes #1001
This adds `abortTest()` helper function to the k6 module. This function when
called inside a script it will

- stop the whole test run and k6 will exit with 107 status code
- stops immediately the VU that called it  and no more iterations are started
- make sure the teardown() is called
- the engine run status is 7 (RunStatusAbortedScriptError)

`(*goja.Runtime).Interrupt` is used for halting script execution and capturing
stack traces for better error message of what is happening with the script.

We introduce InterruptError which is used with `(*goja.Runtime).Interrupt` to
identify interrupts emitted by abortTest(). This way we use special handling of
this type.

Example script is

```js
import { abortTest, sleep } from 'k6';

export default function () {
    // We abort the test on second iteration
    if (__ITER == 1) {
        abortTest();
    }
    sleep(1);
}

export function teardown() {
    console.log('This function will be called even when we abort script');
}
```

abortTest() can be called anywhere in the script.

The following script will fail with the error
```
ERRO[0000] Using abortTest() in the init context is not supported at (...path to the script )init.js:13:43(34)
```

```js
import {
    abortTest
} from 'k6';

abortTest();

export function setup() {
}

export default function () {
    // ... some test logic ...
    console.log('mayday, mayday');
}
```

You can customize the reason for abortTest() by passing values to the function

```js
abortTest("Exceeded expectations");
```

Will emit `"Exceeded expectations"` on the logs

Missing 
 - [ ] Tests
    - [x] Check status code is `107` when the `abortTest()` is called in a script
    - [ ] Wait for `CTRL+C` when `--linger` flag is set
    - [x] Check correct default log message for `abortTest()` without arguments
    - [x] Check correct custom log message like `abortTest("maybday!")`
    - [x] Check teardown is called when a script aborts
